"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. I want to share some of the things I've learned in my very short uh venture into market gardening. First off, I'm over trying to grow tomatoes or I'm sorry, cucumbers in the fall because it just doesn't seem to work out for me. This is the second time I've done it and I don't know what I'm doing wrong. They just don't thrive. And the ones that I plant in the springtime thrive ridiculously. So I'm gonna stick to springtime for cucumbers because all of that space I put towards cucumbers, I could have put towards tomatoes, which are absolutely going ballistic. And I'm gonna have a lot of tomatoes. I'm real excited about that. Most of my garden is tomatoes, so that's good. Uh and I'm gonna grow more beans. Beans grow crazy here. I have a wall of beans and I've been harvesting them for days, and I'm gonna be harvesting them for weeks. It's just a great thing. Green onions, these wild onions right here. I love they grow great, they're delicious, and I need to plant them uh way tighter. So I'm I have a trying to get that going. If you'll see right in this bed, I've also cut it all back. I don't uproot the root uh the weeds, I actually just cut them at their base and use them as molds. And that way uh they grow back because if I'm not growing something there, I want something to grow there, and I'm just gonna let my plants out compete the general growth of the area, and I'll cut it back as I need to. I mean, I'm gonna give my plants a competitive advantage. And uh another thing I've learned uh about this is when you're composting stuff, you have a lot of weird big chunks of uh wood chips and leaves and all sorts of other things in your compost, and you kind of need to filter that out uh a lot. It's just constantly everything in your soil and in your worm pile and everything is the big pieces are rising to the top constantly. So anything that gets buried eventually just kind of finds its way to the top. You need to scrape those off regularly, or you're gonna have problems seeding. Which I had an issue with. So I have a little hand rake I use now. Oh, here it is. And uh oops. This is a regular rake that lost its handle, but all the tines on it were good, so it's my hand rake now, and that helps out a ton. Also, third thing I've learned: if someone offers to help, get their help. There's a zillion things to be done in the garden constantly. Identify what needs to be done, what takes time, what anybody can do, what you can show people quickly how to do, and get that help. Uh, a friend of mine, Rachel, came by the other day and helped me out for three hours, and it was like we did double-time work here. It was awesome. Take the help if it's offered, hold people to the help if they offer it, and have a list of things uh in your head that you can easily give to those people to do so that you're using that for the best. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 1.28,\n      \"end\": 2.88,\n      \"duration\": 1.6,\n      \"confidence\": 0.977,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,\n          \"end\": 1.6,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.977\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 1.6,\n          \"end\": 1.76,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 1.84,\n          \"end\": 2.0,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 2.0,\n          \"end\": 2.32,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 2.32,\n          \"end\": 2.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \".\",\n          \"sta